                    <h2>Introduction to Price Simulation</h2>
                    
                    <p>Changing prices is one of the most impactful decisions a business can make. A price increase can boost revenue, but it can also drive customers away. A price decrease might increase sales volume but reduce profitability. The stakes are high, and traditional "gut feeling" approaches often lead to suboptimal outcomes.</p>
                    
                    <p>This is where price simulation comes in. By using Monte Carlo methods to test thousands of scenarios, you can understand the potential outcomes before making any changes to your actual pricing.</p>
                    
                    <h2>Why Simulate Price Changes?</h2>
                    
                    <p>Traditional approaches to pricing decisions often rely on:</p>
                    
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Competitor analysis:</strong> What are others charging?</li>
                        <li><strong>Cost-plus pricing:</strong> Adding a margin to costs</li>
                        <li><strong>Value-based pricing:</strong> What customers are willing to pay</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p>While these methods are useful, they miss a critical component: understanding how customers will actually respond to price changes. Simulation fills this gap by modeling customer behavior based on historical data.</p>
                    
                    <h2>Step 1: Gather Your Data</h2>
                    
                    <p>The foundation of any good simulation is quality data. You'll need:</p>
                    
                    <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
                        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Required Data Points</h3>
                        <ul class="space-y-2">
                            <li><strong>Historical sales data:</strong> At least 6-12 months of transaction-level data</li>
                            <li><strong>Price history:</strong> Previous price changes and their timing</li>
                            <li><strong>Customer segmentation:</strong> How different customer groups respond</li>
                            <li><strong>Seasonal patterns:</strong> Monthly or quarterly variations</li>
                            <li><strong>Competitor pricing:</strong> How your prices compare to alternatives</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    
                    <p>Export this data as a CSV file from your accounting or CRM system. The more detailed your data, the more accurate your simulation will be.</p>
                    
                    <!-- More content... -->
                    
                    <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-50 to-cyan-50 rounded-2xl p-8 my-12">
